column168: DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING GASOLINE AT A SERVICE STATION. CROWN DRIVER INADVERTENTLY OPENED UNLOADING VALVE ON DISCHARGE LINE WITHOUT LINE (HOSE) BEING CONNECTED TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK COUPLING. APPROX 20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED ONTO SERVICE STATION LOT.  DRIVER WASHED DOWN SERVICE STATION LOT TO DISSIPATE GASOLINE FUMES.  FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO SPILL AND USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP PRODUCT.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM SITE AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED BY ANOTHER DRIVER THAT SMOKE WAS ESCAPING FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER AND DISCOVERED A CLOUD OF VAPOR RELEASING WHEN HE STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE.  EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED AND THE AREA EVACUATED.  SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE ADVISED DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURES AND AUTHORIZED FORWARDING OF EMPTY CANISTER FOR INSPECTION.  DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.  ACCORDING TO THE MEDIA, TWO POLIC OFFICERS WERE ALSO CHECKED.
column172: Metal can, capacity 7 gallons or less

column168: DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TWO PAILS UPON ARRIVAL AT TERMINAL.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND PROVIDED RECOVERY INFORMATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND ADVISED FORWARDING FREIGHT TO CONSIGNEE.
TOP CLOSURE WAS APPARENTLY LOOSE AND RELEASED MATERIAL DURING LOADING. THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE SHIPMENT PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR FORWARDING TO CONSIGNEE.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKIN BY RAIL YARD PERSONNEL. CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE ALL REDUCER FITTINGS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LOOSE AND ALSO THE PAKING GLAND MATERIAL AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE SHAFT WAS LOOSE. FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION, ALL REDUCER FITTINGS AND PACKING MATERIAL WERE TIGHTENED UNTIL THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. CAR WAS THEN RELEASE TO DESTINATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ADVISED THAT THE CAR DEPT WAS INSPECTING CARS IN #7 TRACK FLING YD (COLDWATER ROAD) AND DETECTED ON ODOR OF LP GAS AROUND CAR UTPX 932035. FURTHER INSPECTION. BY THE CAR DEPT WITH THE GASTECH 8800 FOUND CAR TO BE IN A LEAKING CONDITION. I RESPONSED AND INSPECTED CAR UTAX 932035 AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING: A & B END LIQUID LINE PLUGS -LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT 2.VAPOR LINE PLUG LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. 3.GAUGING DEVICE TELL-TALE SAMPLE ASSEMBLY LOOSE 4.GAUGING DEVICE PACKING GLAND NUT LOOSE. TIGHTENED LOOSE FITTINGS AND PLUGS AND CAR WAS SECURED AT 1630 HRS. SHIPPER ADVISED OF EXCEPTION NOTED.

TOTE BIN WAS FOUND LEAKING AT THE POINT OF UNLOADING.  SHIPMENT WAS SET IN HAZMAT AREA ON DOCK AND PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. APPEARS THAT LEAK IS FROM FAULTY SPOUT ON TOTE.  PRODUCT LOSS WAS LESS THAT ONE GALLON.  A DRIP PAN WAS PLACED UNDER THE SPOUT TO CATCH THE DRIP. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE ABF TERMINAL TO TRANSFER PRODUCT INTO OTHER APPROVED CONTAINERS.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS HIRED TO TRANSFER AND TRANSPORT PRODUCT BACK TO THE SHIPPERS FACILITY.
column172: Cage made of wooden frame with wire cover (cont2 only)

column168: TANKER TRUCK HEADING NORTH ON WILLMINTON AVE STOPPED AT STOP SIGN AT CARSON ST INTERSECTION.  THE RUPTURE DISC WAS THOUGHT TO HAVE RUPTURED & HERE BECAUSE THATS WHERE THE TRAIL OF ACID STARTED.  WHEN DRIVER TOOK OFF FROM THE STOP SIGN AND BECAUSE TRAILER IS A CLEAN BORE WITH NO BAFFLES, THE SURGE OF THE PRODUCT RUPTURED THE RUPTURE DISC.  SINCE THE TRAILER IS REAR LOADING THE RUPTURE DISC IS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF TRAILER.  RHONE POULENC WAS NOTIFIED AS TRUCK PULLED IN TO GET OFF STREET.  WHEN DRIVES WHERE ALERTED WHAT HAPPENED BY MOTORIST THEY WERE ONLY 1 BLOCK FROM RHONE POULENC.  RP ALERTED THE PROPER RESPONSE PEOPLE IMMEDIATELY.

DRIVER HAD HOOKED UP AND BEEN PUMPING FOR ABOUT FIVE MINUTES.  WHEN THE HOSE CAME OFF OF THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP BLEW OFF.  HE SHUT DOWN THE PUMP.  CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP A SPILL OF APPROXIAMTELY 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL, THIS PRODUCT WAS SPILL ON CONCRETE AND ASPHALT.
THE HOSE CAME OFF THE FITTING AND SPILLED 1/2 GALLON OF WASTE.  THE HOSE WAS PUT BACK ON AND ABSORBENT TOWELS WERE USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THIS VEHICLE WHICH IS TERMINAL IN BATON ROUGE, LA ON 3-3-93 WAS LOADED WITH 8700 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AT PLACID REFINERY IN PORT ALLEN, LA. AT APPROX 0450 HOURS. PROCEEDED WESTBOUND ON I-10 TO LAFAYETTE, LA.  VEHICLE THEN EXITED I-10 AT AMBASSADOR CAFRY THRUWAY. (APPROX 50 MI WEST OF BATON ROUGE, LA) CAME TO A STOP AT INTERSECTION, TURNED SOUTH ON AMBASSADOR CAFREY PORCEEDED OVER I-10 THEN STOPPED AGAIN FOR TRAFFIC SIGNAL AT 1ST INTERSECTION, APPROX 1/4 MILE SOUTH OF I-10.  PROCEEDED STRAIGHT FOR APPROX 1/4 MI WHERE VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  ACCORDING TO DRIVER AND WITNESSES A LOUD NOISE WAS HEARD, LIKE A TIRE BLOW-OUT OR AN EXPLOSION, BEFORE THE TRUCK TRAILER ROLLED OVER& EXPLODED.  TIRE MARKS AT THE SCENE INDICATE THE VEHICLE DRIFTED OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE PAVED SHOULDER AND OVERTURNED. THE FIFTH WHEEL WAS SEPARATED FROM THE TRUCK AND REMAINED ATTACHED TO THE TRAILER KING PIN.  PROPERTY AUTHORITY 'S AS WELL AS RECOVERY & CLEANUP CREWS WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED IMEDIATELY.  A GREATER EMPHASIS ON DRIVER AWARENESS AND MAINTENANCE WILL BE PRESCIBED.

TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS WERE FOUND DAMAGED UPON ARRIVAL AT TERMINAL.  APPEARS THAT DRUMS HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY FORKLIFT WHILE LOADING.  LOST APPR 27 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WHICH WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL.  ONE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND BOTH WERE PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON OVERPACK EACH AND PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  RECEIVED RETURN AUTHORIZATION FROM THE SHIPPER.

ONE METAL 55 GALLON DRUM ARRIVED AT TERMINAL WITH HAIRLINE CRACK IN THE MIDDLE OF THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 85-GALLON OVERPACK, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. PRODUCT THAT LEAKED FROM CONTAINER EVAPORATED FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.
FIBER DRUM BEING MOVED BY HAND AND DROPPED.

OUR SALES REP WAS REMOVING A 16 GALLON DRUM FROM A CUSTOMER LOCATION BY HAND CART. WHEN HE WENT OVER THE DOOR THRESHOLD THE DRUM FELL AND THE LID CAME OFF. THE DRUM WAS RIGHTED AND THE MATERIAL WAS MOPPED UP. THE SPILL WAS ON A CONCRETE SURFACE & 100% WAS CAPTURED. THE DRUM WAS TO BE LOADED ON OUR ROUTE TRUCK. FUTURE INCIDENTS COULD BE AVOIDED BY SECURING THE DRUM TO THE HAND CART AND PAYING CLOSER ATTENTION THE THE TASK AT HAND.

WHILE ENROUTE DRIVER FOUND THAT DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK. PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER BY A VENDOR. TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND DRIVER PROCEDED TO DESTINATION. RECOVERY DRUM WAS ORDERED AND CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUM WITH PRODUCT AND PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. WE RECEIVED RETURN AUTHORIZATION FROM THE SHIPPER PER KEN HENSEL. APPEARS DRUM EITHER HAD A STRESS FRACTURE OR FAULTY SEAMS. DRUMS SHOULD BE INSPECTED BY SHIPER PRIOR TO USING.

DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO TOTALLY CLOSE THE VALVE, BUT HE DID GET HOSE BACK ON.  PRODUCT LOST WAS CLEANED UP BY THE DRIVER.  MOBILE REPRESENTATIVE, GARY PUETZ WAS PLEASED WITH CLEAN-UP AND HAD NO PROBLEM.  IN THE FUTURE WE WILL ALWAYS MAKE SURE VALVES ARE CLOSED AND IN THE LOCKED POSITION.

THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN TO THE CENTRAL PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER BY UNLOADER TODD GUILFORD WHERE IT WAS PROCESSED FOLLOWING NATIONAL DAMAGE PROCEDURES USING RUBBER GLOVES AND APRON.  NO OUTSIDE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS WERE ON THE PACKAGE.  5 OF 7 INNER CONTAINERS WERE MARKED AS "RADIOACTIVE I".  A ONE PINT GLASS FLASK WAS BROKEN AND LEAKED OUT THE PACKAGE.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS AND PACKAGING WERE PLACED INTO A PLASTIC DMN BAG, ISOLATED, AND HELD FOR CUSTOMER CONTACT FOR MSDS AND POSSIBLE INSPECTION BY THE FAA.

column168: UPON OPENING THE BELLY CARGO COMPARTMENT ON UA FLIGHT 1407/06 MARCH IN ABQ, A VERY STRONG GASOLINE ODOR WAS DISCOVERED. THE ODOR WAS TRACED TO A MAIL BAG. POSTAL OFFICIALS IN ABQ CONFIRMED THAT A PACKAGE IN THE MAIL BAG HAD CONTAINED A PINT OF GASOLINE WHICH LEAKED INTO THE MAIL BAG. (NO GASOLINE WAS FOUND IN THE AIRCRAFT). THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ITEM SENT BY THE SHIPPER WITHOUT PROPER PACKING, MARKING, LABELLING OR DOCUMENTATION. THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE DID HAVE SOME MARKINGS TO INDICATE THAT THE BOX HAD CONTAINED SPRAY PAINT BUT THIS WAS OVERLOOKED BY THE POST OFFICE DURING ACCEPTANCE IN OREGON. THE CONSIGNEE IN RIO RANCHO, NM DOES TESTING OF GASOLINE SAMPLES. HOW MANY MORE ARE SHIPPED THIS SAME WAY AND MAKE IT THRU WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS? UNITED IS FILING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL AVATION REGULATIONS PART 175.45. UNITED MAKES NO DETERMINATION OR ADMISSION BY VIRTUE OF THIS FILING AS TO THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.

A MULTI COMPARTMENTED TANK TRADE CARRING ACETONE SPLIT BETWEEN THE TWO BULKHEADS THAT SEPARATE THE COMPARTMENTS. THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED ON I-55, A SHORT DISTANCE FROM THE CHEMICAL TERMINAL WHERE IT WAS LOADED. AFTER THE TRUCK SPLIT THE DRIVER PULLED TO THE SHOULDER. ILLINOIS TATE PATROL CLOSED THAT PORTION OF THE HIGHWAY TO TRAFFIC. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. DIKED THE LEAKING ACETONE AND FOAMED IT WITH AFFF. A LOCAL BRANCH OF OHM CORP A PRIVATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY ABSORBED THE SPILL MATERIAL AND ARRANGED FOR ITS IMMEDIATE REMOVAL TO A WASTE CHEMICAL INCINERATOR. TANK WAS RECEIVED FROM TRUCKER MARCH 10,1993 WITH NO EXCEPTION NOTED.  THE FOLLOWING DAY, A DRIVER OUR YARD NOTICED A LEAK AROUND THE TANK.  THE INFORMATION WAS GIVEN TO THE SUPERVISOR WHO INVESTIGATED, IDENTIFIED THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT AND HAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL CONTAIN THE SPILL.  HE THEN TIGHTENED THE CAP ON THE TANK.  THE MANAGER OF SPECIAL COMMODITIES WAS THEN NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  HE NOTIFIED THE PRODUCT OWNER AND THE COAST GUARD. THE OWNER INSPECTED THE TANK AND CONTACTED A CONTRACTOR FOR CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL.  THE US COAST GUARD INSPECTED THE TANK THE SPILL AREA AND CONFIRMED APPROVAL OF HANDLING OPERATIONS.  CARRIERS WILL SECURE EQUIPMENT PRIOR TO TRANSPORTING.

TRAILER WAS LOADED IN TEXAS CITY.  DRIVER WASHED OFF LOADING AREA.  WATER RAN INTO CATCH PAN AT REAR OF TRAILER.  DRIVER FAILED TO DRAIN IT.  GUARD AT AMOCO STOPPED TRUCK AT GATE AND THE DRIVER AND GUARD CHECKED IT AND DECIDED IT WAS WATER.  TURCK PROCEEDED TO LAPORTE.  THREE AREAS WERE SPLASHED ON SENS ROAD;  CHECKED AND IT HAD ACIDIC REACTION ON LITMUS PAPER.  AREAS WERE COVERED WITH BICARBONATE AND A VACUUM TRUCK WAS BROUGHT OUT AND AREA CLEANED.  ROAD BETWEEN TEXAS CITY AND LAPORTE WAS CHECKED WITH NO FURTHER CONTAMINATED AREA FOUND.  TEXAS CITY FIRE DEPT CLEANED AREA AT AMOCO PLANT.

THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED INSIDE THE OVERPACK DRUM WITH THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS THEN LABELED AND SENT ON TO A PERMITTED SAFETY-KLEEN RECYCLE CENTER.

column168: DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING 3400 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AT A SERVICE STATION (VA-14).  DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE INTO ONE OF THE TWO 10,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  EACH TANK HAD THE CAPACITY TO HOLD 2800 GALLONS;  5600 GALLONS COMBINED.  THE TWO TANKS ARE MINIFOLDED TOGETHER VIA TWO INCH PIPING.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THROUGH A VISUAL PORT IN THE UNLOADING COUPLER THAT FLOW HAD STOPPED AND ASSUMED UNLOADING WAS COMPLETE.  THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY FITTING AND LEFT HOSE ON THE GROUND.  THE VAPOR RECOVERY FITTING WAS LEFT CONNECTED TO THE TANK. THE PRODUCT HOSE WAS LEFT CONNECTED TO THE DROP FITTING.  THE DRIVER THEN WENT INTO STATION OFFICE TO GET PAPERWORK SIGNED.  WHEN DROPPING INTO AN UNDERGROUND TANK MANIFOLDED TO A SECOND TANK PRESSURE CAN BUILD IN THE TANK/PIPING SYSTEM. IT IS ASSUMED THAT PRESSURE IN THE TANK MAY HAVE CAUSED PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT OF VAPOR RECOVERY FITTING LEFT CONNECTED TO TANK AND DISCONNECTED FROM HOSE. (CONTINUED ON ATTACHED PAGE)
WHILE DISCONNECTING HOSES, PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED.

DRIVER WAS LOADED & ENROUTE TO DELIVERY.  HE STOPPED TO DO HIS TIRE CHECKS & OPENED TRUCK TO CHECK FREIGHT.  NOTICED ODOR WHEN HE OPENED DOOR & SAW LIQUID SITTING ON ONE DRUM.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED DISPATCH.  DISPATCH CALLED SUPERVISORS & HAZMAT PEOPLE.  ALSO CALLED LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TO BLOCK OFF AREA.  WE HAD FIRE DEPARTMENT STAY TILL FREIGHT WAS CHECKED.  WE CALLED ECOLOGY & ENVIRONMENT, INC. TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP.  CLOSEST CLEAN-UP TEAM 4-5 HRS AWAY, PUT THEM ENROUTE.  WHEN THEY ARRIVED MATERIAL ALREADY JELLED TO TOP.  THEY FOUND A LOOSE BUNG CAP.  TIGHTEND IT 1 1/4 TURNS.  THEY FOUND 4 LOOSE BUNG CAPS BETWEEN THE 4 DIFFERENT DRUMS OF CADMIUM.  ALL TOOK 1-2 TURNS TO TIGHTEN.  LOAD SAFE TO TRANSPORT NOW PER BUTCH BEARDSLEY OF EMTECH. EMTECH HAD TO BREAK SEALS TO TIGHTEN BUNG CAPS ON ALL 4 DRUMS.

WHILE UNLOADING INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK, CUSTOMER PERSONNEL ON TOP OF TRAILER DIDN'T INDICATE TO OUR DRIVER THAT THE TRAILER WAS GOING TO OVERFILL.  PRODUCT DID OVERFLOW ONTO THE CONCRETE.  CONSIGNEE RSPONSIBLE FOR CLEAN UP OF SPILL WHICH WAS CONTAINED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR DRIVER HAD EXITED I-95 AND WAS MAKING A RIGHT TURN ONTO WESTMORELAND STREET.  AS HE WAS MAKING THE TURN THE TRAILER WHEELS STRUCK A MOUND OF SNOW AND ICE.  THE TRAILER DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRACTOR AND OVERTURNED. A RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER STRUCK AND OBJECT AT ROADSIDE AND WAS DAMAGED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  ANOTHER TRAILER WAS SENT TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH OUR REPONSE PERSONNEL AND THE CARGO WAS TRANSFERRED.  THE CITY FIRE DEPT. FLUSHED THE AREA.

OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING PRODUCT FROM THE SHIPPER'S STORAGE USING HIS TRACTOR PRODUCT PUMP.  WHEN THE SHIPPER'S TANK EMPTIED OUR DRIVER WENT TO HIS TRACTOR TO REV UP HIS PUMP TO CLEAR THE LOADING LINES OF PRODUCT. WHEN HE REVVED HIS PUMP THE VIBRATION CAUSED THE HOSE LEADING FROM THE PUMP TO THE TRAILER TO DISCONNECT AND PRODUCT STARTED TO ESCAPE FROM OUR TANK TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER ACTIVATED THE REMOTE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF TO STOP THE FLOW.  HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THERE WAS A HEAVY RAIN THAT SPREAD THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND WE ENGAGED A CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL PEOPLE WERE NOTIFIED AND HAVE BEEN OVERSEEING THE CLEAN UP.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE LOADING SITE AND SPOTTED HIS TRAILER FOR LOADING.  HE FAILED TO MAKE SURE THAT THE VALVES WERE CLOSED AND WHEN THE CUSTOMER STARTED TO LOAD THE TRAILER PRODUCT RAN ONTO THE LOADING AREA. OUR DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVES TO STOP THE LOSS.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER.

MECHANICAL DEPT NOTIFIED AT 13:55 ON 3-23-93 THAT TANK WAS LEAKING IN TRAIN STRANDING ON ML 2 IN YARD.  INSPECTED CAR DISCOVERED LEAKING AT TOP UNDER DOME COVER.  ASKED ATM TO HAVE CAR SETOUT AND ISOLATED FOR REPAIR. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND CREW WAS SENT FROM HOUSTON.  THEY INSPECTED CAR AT 24:00 ON 3-23-93, WAS NOT LEAKING.  CREW RETURNED 3-24-93 AND REPAIRED CAR.
DRIVE PARKED UNIT IN FRONT OF HOME.  SOMEONE OPENED VALVE SPILLING FIRST COMPARTMENT CONTENTS TO DITCH.

column168: THE COMMODITY WAS OFFLOADED AT OUR HOUSTON, TEXAS RAMP FACILITY. THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR IMMEDIATELY FROM THE RUPTURED CONTAINER.  WE CLEARED THE AFFECTED AREA IMMEDIATELY AND INITIATED SPILL CONTAINMENT PROCEDURES. UPON ISOLATING THE PACKAGE WE FOUND THAT THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, NOR SHIPPING PAPERS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE REMAINING INNER CONTAINER WE FOUND INFORMATION THAT LEAD US TO CALL THE SHIPPER TO ASK FOR AN MSDS ON THE COMMODITY.  THE LOCAL FAA/CAFSO WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY CAME AND CONFISCATED THE REMAINING BOTTLE AS WELL AS OTHER DOCUMENTATION ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

INVESTIGTION DETERMINED CAN HAD SEEPAGE FROM AROUND CAP.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE CAN MAY HAVE BEEN FILLED TOO FULL.  THE CAN WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY SALVAGE DRUM, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

OUR DRIVER HAD PICKED UP HIS LADING IN PHILADELPHIA AND HAD STOPPED AT KEASBEY, NJ TERMINAL TO GO ON LAYOVER.  DURING A YARD CHECK AT THE TERMINAL IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MATERIAL WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BELLY OF OUR TRAILER.  A CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO CATCH THE MATERIAL AND OUR PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND THE CARGO WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR PERSONNEL AND THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED AND UPON INSPECTION A CASE OF OIL WELL CARTRIDGES SAID TO CONTAIN 50 INDIVIDUALS PIECES HAD ONE PIECE MISSING.  A COMPLETE INVESTIGATION DID NOT INDICATE WHERE OR WHEN THE ONE CARTRIDGE HAD FALLEN OUT OF THE BOX.  THE SERVICE CENTERS THAT THE SHIPMENT MOVED THROUGH AND THE TRAILERS THAT HAD CONTAINED THE BOX WERE INSPECTED TO SEE IF THE CARTRIDGE COULD BE FOUND.  AS OF THE DATE OF SUBMISSION OF THIS REPORT, THE CARTRIDGE HAD NOT BEEN FOUND.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON CLAYTON ROAD APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION OF CLAYTON ROAD AND JAMES ROAD.  CLAYTON ROAD "T" INTERSECTS WITH JAMES ROAD AND IS CONTROLLED BY A STOP SIGN.  OUR DRIVER APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION TOO FAST FOR THE CONDITION (WET PAVEMENT), APPLIED BRAKES BUT SKIDDED PAST THE STOP SIGN INTO THE INTERSECTION.  AS NOTED PREVIOUSLY, CLAYTON ROAD IS NOT A THROUGH ROAD AND OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO TURN TO THE LEFT ONTO JAMES ROAD, BUT SKIDDED OFF THE PAVEMENT INTO THE SHOULDER AND OVERTURNED.  NO MATERIAL WAS SPILLED OR RELEASED AT ANY TIME DURING OR AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, NONE DURING THE TRANS-LOAD PROCESS.  ONE HOUSEHOLD WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.

ON SUNDAY 3-7-93 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 AM, THE PLANT BEGAN TO UNLOAD CAUSTIC SODA FROM T/C UTLX 85195 SUPPLIED BY HCI CHEMTECH INDUSTRIES IN MEMPHIS, TN.  WHEN CAR WAS PRESSURED FOR UNLOADING THE OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING WHERE THE WEEL FRAME ENTERS THE INSULATION JACKET ON THE B END OF THE CAR.  THE PLANT OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE FLOW, TOOK PRESSURE OFF THE CAR AND CONTAINED THE LEAKS WITH PLASTIC BUCKETS.  THE CAR WAS SPOTTED ON A METAL CATCH PAN THEREFORE NO MATERIAL WAS ALLOWED TO GO TO AN UNCONTROLLED SURFACE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES DUE TO THE LEAK AND NO REPORTABLE QUANTITY SPILLED.  OPERATIONS MANAGER AND PLANT MANAGER WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  THE ORIGIN OF THE LEAK COULD NOT BE DETERMINED AS THIS CAR HAD AN INSULATION JACKET.  THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR MADE THE DECISION TO PUMP THE MATERIAL OUT OF THE CAR TO THE STORAGE TANK WITHOUT THE USE OF PRESSURE.  I CONTACTED HCI CHEMTEC IN MEMPHIS, TN TO ADVISE THEM OF OUR SITUATION AND WAHT ACTION WE WERE TAKING TO SAFELY UNLOAD THE RAILCAR.  WE WERE CONTACTED SEVERAL TIMES BY CHEMTEC DURING OUR UNLOADING TIME TO INSURE WE WERE NOT INCURRING ANY PROBLEMS. THE UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 PM SUNDAY 3-7-93.  THERE WAS STILL A SMALL AMOUNT OF SEEPAGE COMING FROM THE INSULATION OF THE CAR. PLASTIC BUCKETS REMAINED UNDER THE LEAKS FOR CONTAINMENT.

column168: THE PROCESS WAS TO LOAD APPROX 5500 GALLONS ON TANK TRAILER.  LOADER SPOTTED TRAILER, INSPECTED FOR CLEANLINESS AND THAT ALL PARTS OR EXTERNAL VALVES WERE IN PLACE AND CLEAN.  SATISIFIED WITH THIS REQUIREMENTS HE HOOKED LOADING ARM TO THE BOTTOM OF TRAILER AT DISCHARGE LINE AND BEGAN PUMPING OF PRODUCT.  HALF WAY THROUGH LOAD HE NOTICED DRIPPAGE AROUND EXTERNAL VALVE, SO HE TIGHTENED RETAIN CLAMP AND DRIPPAGE STOPPED.  MOMENTS LATER HE NOTICED DRIPPAGE AT SAME AREA AGAIN.  THIS TIME HE TAPPED WING-NUT ON CLAMP WITH AIR FITTING AND LEAKAGE STOPPED, BUT SECONDS LATER ENTIRE EXTERNAL VALVE STEM BLEW-OUT.  LOADER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF PUMP AND THEN USING EMERGENCY BREAK-AWAY CLOSED INTERNAL VALVE.  CLEAN UP BEGAN BY USING SKIMMER VACUUM AND RETAINING IN DRUMS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0730, MARCH 22, 1993, I WAS INFORMED OF ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR.  NATX 72782, ON THE WEST END OF 124 TRACK.  THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE BASE OF THE SAFETY VALVE.  I COULD NOT TIGHTEN THE BOLTS.  I THEN REPLACED ALL FOUR (4) BOLTS THAT HOLD THE SAFETY VALVE DOWN AND THE ODOR STOPPED. I CHECKED WITH THE GAS TRACK LEAK DETECTOR.

DOCKWORKER NOTED RESIDUE ON THE TOP OF ONE CONTAINER, SWEPT IT UP AND PLACED IN INTO AN UNSECURED CONTAINER.  THE MATERIAL LATER REACHED WITH OTHER MATERIALS INSIDE THE CONTAINER AND THE AREA WAS ISOLATED UNTIL CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE CONSULTED.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE THE SPILL AND CLEANUP.

DRIVER NOTICED LEAK AT TRUCK STOP.  LARCO ENVIRONMENTAL CAME TO SCENE, PROTECTED, CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP SPILL AND CLEANED TRAILER.  CAUSE OF SPILL APPEARED TO BE A FATIGUE FRACTURE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON MARCH 11, 1993, ERS PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO A SPILL INCIDENT AT 11921 US 24 EAST OF I-469 IN ALLEN COUNTY, INDIANA.  UPON ARRIVAL ERS PERSONNEL FOUND ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION THAT HAD LEAKED AN ESTIMATED 10 TO 15 GALLONS IN THE WEST BOUND LANE OF US 24.  THE ALLEN COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM HAD ROLLED THE DRUM SO THE CRACK WAS AT THE TOP AND BLOCKED THE DRUM TO PREVENT IT FROM ROLLING.  THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE FROZE TO THE ASPHALT IN AN AREA APPROXIMATELY EIGHT FEET LONG AND TWO FEET WIDE. THERE WAS A TOTAL OF FOUR DRUMS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE IN THE LOAD, HOWEVER ONLY ONE LEAKED.  A COPY OF THE MSDS SHEET IS PRESENTED IN APPENDIX A. FOUR LARGE BATTERIES (I.E. 600 LBS EACH) WERE ON THE LOAD.  ALL FOUR WERE THROWN OUT OF THE TRUCK INTO THE DRIVEWAY AND YARD.  IT WAS NOTED THAT ONE OF THE BATTERIES HAD A CRACK IN THE UPPER CORNER OF THE CASING.  IT WAS WET AROUND THE CRACK AND IT APPEARED THAT VERY LITTLE ACID WAS RELEASED. A COPY OF THE MSDS SHEET IS PRESENTED IS APPENDIX B.  THERE WERE A TOTAL OF SEVEN 5 GALLON CONTAINERS OF KODAK RA 2000 DEVELOPER ON THE LOAD. ALL SEVEN CONTAINER WERE RUPTURED AND SPILLED ONTO THE DRIVEWAY AND INTO THE YARD CONTAMINATING AN APPROXIMATE 15 FEET BY 20 FEET AREA.  A COPY OF THE MSDS SHEET IS PRESENTED IN APPENDIX C.  THERE WERE FOUR 5 GALLON PAILS OF PAINT ON THE LOAD.  ALL FOUR RUPTURED AND CONTAMINATED AN ESTIMATED 20 FEET BY 25 FEET AREA OF THE DRIVEWAY AND YARD.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPING PAPER IS PRESENTED IN APPENDIX D.  ERS PERSONNEL UTILIZED SCRAPPERS AND SQUARE POINT SHOVELS TO BEGIN REMOVAL OF THE FROZEN SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  THIS PROCEDURE WAS NOT WORKING WELL AND WAS HALTED.  A BACKHOE WAS UTILIZED TO OVERPACK THE FOUR DRUMS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE INTO 85 GALLON POLY-OVERPACKS. THE SUN BEGAN TO THAW THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE ON THE ASPHALT. SLIK-WIK ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO ABSORB AND CONTROL THE SPREADING OF THE THAWED SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  SEVERAL ONE GALLON CONTAINERS OF WC-853 ANTIFOAM CLEANER WAS FOUND IN THE SPILL AREA.  ERS PERSONNEL DID NOT LOCATE ANY RUPTURED OR BROKEN CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM.  SLIK-WIK ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO THE GENERAL SPILL AREA.  A BACKHOE AND SHOVELS WERE UTILIZED TO EXCAVATED THE SPILL AREA.  THE SOLIDIFIED MATERIAL WERE LOADED INTO A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AND TRANSPORTED TO MERRITT/HESS IN AUBURN, INDIANA.  THE ALLEN COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM'S CHEMICAL PROTECTIVE CLOTHING WAS ALSO PLACED IN THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER.  A COPY OF A SITE MAP IDENTIFYING THE EXCAVATION IS PRESENTED IN APPENDIX E. OVERLAND TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS INC ARRIVED WITH A TRAILER TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS REMAINING IN THE DAMAGED TRAILER, PICK UP THE FOUR OVERPACK DRUMS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, THE WC-853 ANTIFOAM CONTAINERS AND THE FOUR BATTERIES.  MS. CARLA CLIFFORD WITH OVERLAND TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS, INC INDICATED THE MAHUFACTURERS OF THE PRODUCTS WOULD ACCEPT THE PRODUCTS THAT WERE CONTAINED IN THE DRUMS.  OVERLAND PERSONNEL PICKED UP THE MATERIALS. THE DRIVEWAY WAS RESTORED

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: DOCKWORKER NOTICED A STRONG ODOR UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR FOR UNLOADING AND FOUND ONE DAMAGED CARTON.  SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED AND THE AREA ISOLATED.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AS INSTRUCTED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSAL.

MATERIAL WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A LOOSE FITTING THAT HAD APPARENTLY NOT BEEN COMPLETELY TIGHTENED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  THE AREA WAS ISOALTED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  CHEMCTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR INSTRUCTIONS AND THE SHIPPER ADVISED CONTRACTOR WOULD RESPOND TO SCENE TO REPLACE FAULTY FITTINGS.

DURING UNLOADING, DOCKWORKER NOTED ONE DRUM LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL FROM THE SEAL ONTO THE LID OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED.  THE SHIPPER CALLED AND ADVISED HANDLING AND DISPOSITION PROCEDURES.

THERE WERE FOUR CANS OF PAINT INSIDE A CARDBOARD BOX.  THE CANS WERE SECURED WITH CLIPS ON THEIR LIDS.  THE VIBRATION OF ROAD TRAVEL CAUSED THE LIDS TO BECOME UNSECURED.  THIS RESULTED IN THE SPILLAGE OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX.
LOOSE CAP ON 1 GALLON SPILLING IN BOX.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT LOADSIDE.  2 OF 24 CANS WERE CRUSHED. THE UNDAMAGED PORTION WAS SENT ON.  THE DAMAGED PORTION WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING PROPER HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND WET DURING UNLOAD.  ONE OF TWELVE PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD A FAULTY CAP.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZMAT DISPOSAL/PROCEDURES.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON BOXLINE #4 SLIDE.  IT WAS DAMP WHICH GAVE CAUSE TO SUSPECT SPILLAGE.  BOX WAS PLACED IN SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT TO THE DOT COMPLIANCE CENTER.  PPE WAS DONNED. UPON INSPECTION PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO HAVE 1 LITER GLASS JAR BROKEN.  SINCE THERE WERE NO INTERNAL PARTIONS CAUSE OF CRACKING WAS DUE TO FRAGILE AGAINST HARD OBJECT.  MOST OF THE LIQUID WAS EVAPORATED OR ABSORBED INTO THE CARDBOARD.  DAMAGED JAR WAS REMOVED, REMAINING CONTENTS REPACKED IN ORIGINAL BOX, THEN PLACED IN ANOTHER BOX WITH A SUFFICIENT AMOUNT OF CUSHOINING AND RTS.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN UNLOAD.  ONE GALLON CAN HAD LOOSE LID. THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE. A DIR WAS COMPLETED.

THE COMPLETE PARCEL WAS RECONTAINERIZED IN A 5 GALLON BUCKET.  THE DAMAGED PORTION WAS SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS CAGE AND THE REST OF THE PARCEL WAS REPACKED ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  ISP CARD WAS PREPARED AND SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR THEIR FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

THE PACKAGE CAME OUT OF THE TRAILER, NOTICED WET PARCEL.  PUT INTO A SPILL TUB AND OPENED THE PACKAGE.  THE MERCHANDISE WAS DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO DOT SPECIFICATIONS AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  AN ISP CARD WAS PREPARED AND SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR THEIR FOLLOWUP WITH THE SHIPPER.

column168: WHEN TANK CAR NATX 269 WAS COUPLED INTO OTHER CARS IN TRAIN, A SMALL QUANTITIY OF LADING SURGED THROUGH A DEFECTIVE SECTION OF THE MANWAY GASKET, SPLASHING A TRAINMAN.  THE CAR WAS NOT MOVED UNTIL THE GASKET WAS REPLACED.  AFTER THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SCHEDULED MOVEMENT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON MARCH 23, 1993, THE INBOUND CREW OF TRAIN 01-261-21 SET OUT TANK CAR NDYX 35338 AT TRINIDAD, DUE TO POSSIBLE LEAKAGE INDICATED BY AN AMMONIA ODOR AND LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER. FARMLAND INDUSTRIES IN ENID, OKLAHOMA.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED TO CARGO TANKS TO TRINIDAD FOR POSSIBLE TRANSFER OF THE LADING. UPON ARRIVAL AT TRINIDAD, THE CARGO TANK DRIVERS INDICATED THAT THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE CAR OR LEAKAGE OF THE SPACE BETWEEN THE TANK SHELL AND TANK JACKET.  THEY SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS ON MARCH 24, 1993, THREE CREW MEMBERS OF TRAIN 01-262-24 NOTICED THE ODOR OF AMMONIA AND INDICATED FEELING NAUSEAOUS, DIFFICULTY IN BREATHING, HEADACHES AND TIGHTNESS IN CHEST. THE THREE CREW MEMBERS WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE THEY WERE X-RAYED, TREATED AND RELEASED.  ON MARCH 25, 1993, A SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE AND RESPONDERS FROM THE ASSOCIATION OF AMERICAN RAILROADS, THE COLORADO HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE LAS ANIMAS COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A DEFECTIVE O-RING IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND LOOSE NUTS ON THE STUD BOLTS SECURING THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE TO THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THESE DEFICIENCIES WERE CORRECTED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO FINAL DESTINATION.

FREIGHT CAME INTO THE CHARLOTTE, NC TERMINAL WITH 2 LIDS LEAKING, DOCK PUT FREIGHT IN OS&D DEPT.  SINCE THE TWO LIDS WERE ALREADY LOOSE I WAS ABLE TO DIRECT THE LIQUID ON TOP OF THE TWO DRUMS BACK INTO THE SPOUT AND THEN TIGHTENED THE TWO DRUMS.  NONE OF THE LIQUID GOT ON THE TRAILOR, WHSE., OR DOCKPERSON.  THEIR WAS NO PRODUCT LOSS, WE USED MASKS AND RUBBER GLOVES FOR PROTECTION.

TRAILER ARRIVED ON RAMP AT DESTINATION AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING. TRAILER WAS ISOLATED TO CONTAIMENT PIT WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE DRIPPING LIQUID. CONTRACTOR HANDLED RELOADING, CLEANING AND OVERPACKING. A SECOND TIER OF 8 DRUMS ON PALLETS WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN INSUFFICIENTLY BRACED WITH ONLY TWO 2X4S ACROSS THE DRUMS. BRACING WAS BROKEN AND DRUMS WERE ROLLING AROUND ON TOP OF FIRST LAYER.  FRICTION/RUBBING CAUSED A SMALL HOLE IN EACH OF TWO DRUMS. DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND RELOADED. LOOSE BUNGS WERE FOUND ON NUMEROUS FIRST LAYER DRUMS, USUALLY WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE DRUM. FIRST LAYER DRUMS HAD NO BLOCKING & BRACING APPLIED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR UNIT WAS AUDIDING AN AUTOMOBILE ENTERING ROADWAY, WAS STRUCK AND FORCED INTO CENTER GUARD RAIL, JACK-KNIFED, ROLLED OVER AND COMPLETELY BURNED CARGO TANK AND CARGO.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON PRIMARY UNLOAD.  THE 1 GALLON CONTAINER HAD A LOOSE LID.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND SENT TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS HEADED NORTHBOUND ON BROADWAY EXTENSION IN KANSAS CITY, MO SOUTH OF THE MO HWY 9 INTERCHANGE.  HE WAS IN LEFT OF TWO NORTHBOUND LANES.  LEFT SIDE OF UNIT MADE CONTACT W/CENTER CONCRETE DIVIDING WALL WHILE NEGOTIATING AN S-TYPE CURVE.  UNIT SKIDDED NORTH ON CENTER DIVIDING WALL SKIDDING TO THE RIGHT AND UPSETTING ON THE UNIT'S RIGHT SIDE.  THE TRAILER RIPPED OPEN, SO WHEN UNIT FLIPPED, FUEL BEGAN LEAKING & UNIT IGNITED.  TRAILER & TRACTOR  CAME TO REST UNDER LARGE TRUSS HIGHWAY SIGN AND HIGH VOLTAGE POWER LINES.  THE FLAMES DESTROYED SIGN & BURNED POWER LINES.  MIXTURE OF GASOLINE AND FIRE DESTROYING FOAM DRAINED OVER EMBANKMENT CAUSING GROUND CONTAMANATION WHICH HAD TO BE REMOVED PER KANSAS CITY HEALTH REGULATIONS.  NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN WRECKAGE OR CAME INTO CONTACT WITH BURNING TRACTOR/TRAILER.  DRIVER OF UNIT SUSTAINED MINOR BURNS TO FACE, WAS TREATED, THEN RELEASED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 61 ON HIS RETURN TRIP TO THUNDER BAY FROM SUPERIOR WINCONSIN WITH A LOAD OF UNLEADED FUEL.  AT AROUND SCHROEDER MINNESOTA HE OBSERVED THAT IT WAS SNOWING AND BY THE TIME HE PASSED THROUGH TOFTE HE DECIDED TO PULL OFF THE ROAD AND WAIT OUT THE STROM.  APPROXIMATELY TWO MILES NORTH OF TOFTE HE OBSERVED A SIGN FOR A REST AREA AHEAD ON THE RIGHT HAND SIDE OF THE ROAD.  HE SLOWED HIS VEHICLE TO A CRAWL AND STARTED TO ENTER THE REST AREA WHEN HE FELT A TUG FROM THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRAILER.  WHEN HE LOOKED IN HIS MIRROR HE NOTICED THAT THE TRAILER WHEELS WERE SLIDING TO THE RIGHT DOWN A BANK AND THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER STARTED PULLING BACKWARD.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BOTH ROLLED OVER LANDING ON THE ROOF.  THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT CAUSED THE WINDOWS ON THE TRUCK TO POP OUT.  THE DRIVER THEN TURNED OFF THE LIGHTS AND IGNITION AND CRAWLED OUT.  ONCE CLEAR OF THE CAB THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE ON FIRE.  HE ATTEMPTED TO RETRIEVE THE EXTINGUISHER BUT COULD NOT REACH IT.  AS HE CLIMBED BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY A VEHICLE CAME ALONG WHICH TURNED OUT TO BE THE SON OF THE FIRE WARDEN.  HE CLIMBED INTO THE VEHICLE AND THEY DROVE A QUARTER MILE TO THE FIRE WARDENS HOUSE.  THE TOFTE AND OTHER AREA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE FUEL FROM THE TANKER FLOWED DOWN A DITCH TOWARDED LAKE SUPERIOR CAUSING A FEW TREES TO BURN AS WELL AS SOME GRASS AND SHRUB BRUSH.  AT SOME POINT THE DECISION WAS MADE TO LET THE FUEL BURN RATHER THAN LET IT FLOW INTO THE LAKE.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO MURPHY OIL AND THEY CONTACTED OSI TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  THE MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY WAS CONTACTED AND THEY CALLED IN THE COAST GUARD AS WELL AS DISPATCHING A REPRESENTATIVE FROM MINNEAPOLIS.  THE COAST GUARD WAS LATER CANCELLED.  THE OSI TEAM RESPONDED AND CONTACTED A LOCAL EQUIPMENT OPERATOR TO DIG SEVERAL DITCHES WHERE THEY PLACED BOOMS TO CONTROL ANY FUEL THAT WAS HEADING FOR LAKE SUPERIOR.  THEY THEN CONTINUED TO CONTAIN THE AREA AND PROCEEDED WITH THE CLEANUP.  THEY WERE INFORMED AT THE SCENE TO CONTINUE WITH THEIR CLEANUP TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY.  A CALL WAS ALSO PLACED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTRE, REPORT NO 163294 REFERS.  THEY INFORMED US THAT THEY WOULD ENSURE THAT ALL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

THE FOLLOWING IS THE RESULTS OF THE INVESTIGATION CONCERNING A SPILLAGE OF XYLENE ON MARCH 10,1993 AT OUR CUSTOMER'S (FERRO CORP) LOCATION. IT HAS BEEN REPORTED TO ME THAT OUR DRIVER (ADEN WEAVER) HAD UNLOADED THE ISOPROPANOL FIRST WITHOUT ANY DIFFICULTIES. ADEN WAS ACCOMPAINED BY FERRO'S PERSONNEL, DENNIS SHEELER, THE ENTIRE TIME OF UNLADING. AT THE BEGINNING OF UNLOADING XYLENE, A SMALL SPRAY OF PRODUCT WAS BEING FORCED OUT A PIN HOLE IN ONE OF OUR TWENTY-GOOT SECTIONS OF HOSE. THIS SPILLAGE WAS NOTICED IMMEDIATELY NAD ADEN SHUT DOWN THE PRODUCT PUMP TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. ADEN ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF XYLENE WAS RELEASED AND THIS PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING AREA. THE DIKE AREA ALSO CONTAINED WATER WHICH PROBABLY ACCOUNTS FOR THE NINE (9) GALLONS RECOVERED BY CUSTOMER. ADEN DISCONNECTED DAMAGED HOSE WAS DISREGARDED AND THE REMAINING XYLENE WAS THEN UNLOADED FROM THE TANKER INTO THE CUSTOMER'S TANK. INTERSTATE CHEMICAL TRACTORS ARE ALL EQUIPPED WITH ROPER PUMPS FOR UNLOADING SOLVENTS AND THESE PUMPS WILL PRODUCE A RATING OF 25 TO 40 PSI. OUR HOSES ARE CROSS LINK POLYETHYLENE AND ARE RATED FOR 150 PSI, SO THERE IS AN ADEQUATE PSI RATIO BETWEEN WHAT THE PUMP CAN DELIVER AND WHAT OUR HOSES CAN ENDURE. TO ANSWER THE QUESTION OF WHY THE HOSE FAILED? IT IS STILL UNKNOWN, MAYBE THE FAILURE WAS DUE TO AGE, USE, OR POSSIBLY PUNCTURED SOMEHOW.

VII & VIII ABOVE:  NO PACKAGING FIALURE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. THIS WAS A TANK OVERFILL FROM AN ABOVE GROUND TANK.  OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FUEL OIL FROM OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER INTO AGWAY'S ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  UPON ARRIVAL, OUR DRIVER HAD TAKEN STICK READINGS OF THE AMOUNT OF FUEL ALREADY IN AGWAY'S TANK.  INVESTIGATION SHOWS THAT OUR DRIVER USED AN INCORRECT TANK CONVERSION CHART WHEN CALCULATING IF HIS LOAD WOULD FIT.  AS SOON AS THE FUEL CAME OUT THE VENT, OUR DRIVER STOPPED THE PRODUCT FLOW.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE ABOVE GROUND TANKS STEEL DYKE.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED, REFERENCE #9213368.  CLEAN-UP INVOLVES VACUUMING THE FUEL OUT OF THE DYKE.

column168: ON 3-17-93 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, MATT RAGER, REPORTED A UNIT LOAD DEVICE AT THE HAZMAT SORT GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS SETTING IN A SECURE AREA OUTSIDE THE HAZMAT SORT.  NEAL VAN SAUN, HAZMAT SPECIALIST, DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASK TO INVESTIGATE THE CONTENTS OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE. INSIDE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WERE FOUR PIECES OF FREIGHT.  ONE OF THE PIECES OF FREIGHT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THIS FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED "PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1210."  UPON INVESTIGATING THE INNER CONTENTS, I, TONY FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, FOUND INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX A PLASTIC RECEPTICLE WITH A FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE, WITH A CAPACITY OF 2 LITERS.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE CLOSURE CAME OFF OF THE RECEPTICLE CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO LEAK.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: A SIDE-SWIPING COLLISION OCCURRED IN ROCKPORT YARD AT 2050 ON 9 MARCH 93. TANK CAR GATX 90810 WAS PUNCTURED IN ITS "A" HEAD ON THE L SIDE BY THE "B" COUPLER OF TANK CAR GATX 90774, THE ADJACENT CAR.  THE COLLISION RESULTED FROM A MISALIGNED SWITCH.  THE LEAKING CAR WAS TRANSFERRED BY CONRAIL'S FLEXI-FLO TERMINAL PERSONNEL INTO CARGO TANKS.  THIS CAR HAD ROLLED 10 DEGREES TO ITS L SIDE AS BOX CAR RBOX 35542, ON THE ADJACENT TRACK HAD ITS "AR" SIDE LEANING AGAINST THE "BR" SIDE OF GATX 90810. TANK CAR GATX 90774, SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, HAD ROLLED 90 DEGREES TO ITS L SIDE AND WAS LAYING ACROSS THE TRACKS WITH TANK JACKET DAMAGE.  NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAK WAS NOTED BY B OF E INSPECTOR T. J. MANNAS.  HOWEVER, SINCE TRANSFER FORCES WERE ON HAND, THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED FROM GATX 90774 INTO CARGO TANK.

PRO 803-140995 - 1 HM HYDROCHLORIC ACID CORROSIVE MATERIAL UN1789, 28 LBS WAS LOADED IN THE NOSE OF TRLR 15-1032.  PRO 408-906223 FOR MARTIN TRUCK CENTER WAS LOADED AGAINST THE ABOVE PRO.  THE MARTIN TRUCK CENTER WAS AUTO PARTS IRON OR STEEL.  THIS SHIPMENT CAUSED THE DAMAGE.  THE PARTS WERE SHOVED INTO THE CARTON OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CAUSING ONE GLASS BOTTLE TO BREAK AND LEAK. SHIPPERS' REP, WINDELL ALLEN ASKED THAT WE DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL LOCALLY OR TO DONATE IT TO A SCHOOL OR COLLEGE OR TO ANY INDUSTRIAL TRAINING LAB. I CALLED LAMAR UNIVERSITY BIOLOGY LAB 409-880-7011.  MS LINDA FONTENOT SAID THEY LAMAR UNIVERSITY COULD USE IT AND SHE WAS GETTING READY TO ORDER SOME OF THIS FREIGHT.  WE WILL DONATE THIS TO LAMAR UNIVERSITY LAB AND DOCUMENT IT AND HAVE THEIR SIGNATURE ON FILE WITH THIS REPORT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE 1 WAS WESTBOUND ON HWY 18, ENROUTE TO MILFORD, IA. TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY. WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE ADVERSE WITH THE ROAD COVERED WITH SNOW AND ICE.  VEHICLE 2 TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON HWY 18 SWERVED TO MISS A DOG CROSSING THE ROAD AND TRIED TO RETURN TO HER LANE.  AT THIS TIME, THE DRIVER LOST TRACTION, AND HER VEHICLE STARTED TO SLIDE SIDEWAYS INTO VEHICLES 1'S PATH.  VEHICLE 1 STRUCK VEHICLE 2'S LEFT REAR HALF, AND THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WENT INTO THE DITCH.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER LEADED OUT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY BY PUTTING SPEEDY-DRY ON IT.  THE IOWA STATE POLICE INVESTIGATED THE ACCIDENT.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED BY PHONE ON MARCH 22, 1993 AND IS COVERED BY INCIDENT NUMBER 163352.  HWY 18 WAS CLOSED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. THE IOWA DNR INVESTIGATED.

MARKGRIFFITH, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX TOINVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS. INSIDE THERE WAS A METAL RECEPTICLE THATCONTAINED "CPVC", WHICH IS AN ADHESIVE FOR PLASTIC PIPE. THE FRONT AND THE BACKOF THIS METAL RECEPTICLE STATED THAT THIS MATERIAL WAS "EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE".THIS METAL, ONE QUART RECEPTICLE HAD A SCREW-TYPE WITH CLIPS TO SECURE THECLOSURE. THE LABEL ON IT STATED THAT IT WAS "PRIMER". THERE WAS SOME OTHERMISCELLANEOUS PLASTIC PARTS CONTAINED INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THERE WERE NOMARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TOINDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT ISAT THE HAZ-MAT SORT IN THE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS CABINET PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: MANAGER D. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED THAT UTLX 777 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATION.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS A DUAL COMPARTMENT TANK WITH TOLUENE IN THE SECOND "B" COMPARTMENT.  THE "A" COMPARTMENT HAD TORN MANWAY GASKET MATERIAL WHICH ALLOWED A 6-8 INCH GAP BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  THE GAP WAS REPAIRED BY PLACING GORE-TEX MATERIAL IN PLACE OF THE TORN GASKET.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURED.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SA/HM) J. JARA WAS NOTIFIED THAT APLS 278811 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE DEPT. AND CHEMTREC HAD BEEN NOTIFIED.  SA/HM JARA RESPONDED AND OH MATERIAL WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND.  OH MATERIAL RESPONDED AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS IMPROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT ONE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS LEAKING PRODUCT.  THE LEAK WAS A 3/4" CRACK ABOUT 3" UP FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A SHARP OBJECT, POSSIBLY THE EDGE OF A FORK LIFT.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE AN OVERPACK AND LEFT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  RESIDUE WAS CLEANED OFF THE DECK OF THE TRAILER AND A HOLD WAS PLACED ON THE TRAILER UNTIL IT WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.

R.M. STINE, REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, INSPECTED CAR GATX 19527 AND NOTED A VAPOR LEAK FROM THE "REGO" SAFETY VALVE.  THE TANK WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE 60 PSI PRESSURE;  ASSUMED LEAKAGE CAUSED BY DEFECTIVE O RING.  THE STEM GUIDE WAS REMOVED AND REMOVAL OF RETAINER WAS ATTEMPTED, HOWEVER, TURNING OF THE RETAINER NUT CAUSED THE VALVE STEM TO ROTATE (NOTE: THE RETAINER NUT HAD A DEEP CHISEL CUT INDICATING SOMEONE HAD PREVIOUSLY OVERTIGHTENED THE NUT).  DEMKOTE RUST SOLVENT WAS SPRAYED ON AREA AND STEM GUIDE WAS REAPPLIED.  ON 03/09/93, BOE CHEIF INSPECTOR A.D. MATY ASSISTED AND HELD VALVE STEM WITH VICE GRIP PLIERS AND WAS ABLE TO REMOVE THE RETAINER NUT. THE RUST WAS REMOVED FROM THE VALVE SEAT AND RETAINER AND NEW O-RING WAS APPLIED WHICH SECURED LEAK.  JACKET WAS STENCILLED "SAFETY VALVE TEST 1/90, DUE 96" WHICH WAS INCORRECT.  GENERAL AMERICAN TRANSPORTATION, CHICAGO IL, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THE VALVE WAS TESTED IN JANUARY 1991 BY FRIT CAR AND EQUIPMENT, BREWTON, AL.  TEST DATE WAS INCORRECT AND THE "DUE DATE"  WAS CORRECT.      BILL GASSON OF CHEMTREC AND JACK CURRY OF FARMLAND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  MR. CURRY ADVISED THAT THE VALVE WILL BE CHANGED AFTER CAR IS UNLOADED.

UPON ARRIVAL SA/HM CERDA NOTED A SMALL AREA ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR THAT WAS WET WITH PRODUCT.  THE MANWAY COVER HAD A MUSHROOM TYPE SAFETY VENT. ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  LOIS LARSON OF J.R. SIMPLOT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON MARCH 19,1993, A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER WAS RECEIVED AT THE LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. FACILITY IN REIDSVILLE, NC. ON MANIFIEST DOCUMENT #93114.  THE ROLL-OFF WAS IMMEDIATELY INSPECTED UPON ARRIVAL AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  IT WAS PLACED IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  ALL LEAKING MATERIAL WAS ABSORED FROM THE PARKING LOT AND PLACED IN THE ROLL-OFF.  THE GENERATOR AND TRANSPORTER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE LEAK.  A QUALITY CONTROL CHECK OF THE MATERIAL FOUND IT TO CONTAIN FREE STANDING LIQUID. SOLIDIFICATION OF THE MATERIAL WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY BLOWING KILN DUST INTO THE TARPED ROLL-OFF AND USING A TRACKHOE TO MIX THE MATERIAL.  THE ADDITION OF THE KILN DUST REQUIRED THAT A PORTION OF THE SOLIDIFIED LOAD BE TRANSFERRED TO A SECOND ROLL-OFF.  PRIOR TO THE SOLIDIFICATION/TRANSFER OCCURING, THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS POLYLINED.  FOLLOWING COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER, THE TRACKHOE BUCKET WAS DECONTAMINATED AND THE DECON WASH SOLIDIFIED IN THE ROLL-OFF.  THE PLASTIC WAS COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF IN ONE OF THE ROLL-OFFS.

ON 3/24/93, BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN RAILROAD CONDUCTOR ROBERT HARRIS NOTICED THAT A TANK CAR (UTLX 014546) WAS LEAKING.  CAR CONTAINED SULFURIC ACID. THE LEAKING TANK CAR HAD BEEN SET OUT ON THE HORSE TRACK AT WOODWARD, AL. BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN RAILROAD TRANSPORATION SUPERINTENDENT JOHN D'ALESIO AND TRANSPORTAION TRAINMASTER RAY T. FANCHER WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. THERE WAS ONLY AN OCCASIONAL DRIP FROM THE CAR.  LIME WAS PLACED UNDER LEAK TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACIDITY.  CAR HAD BEEN SHIPPED BY THE DOE RUN COMPANY, HERCULANEUM, MO BY SHRIEVE CHEMICAL.  MR. JOHN SARGINGER OF SHRIEVE CHEMICAL WAS CONTACTED AND ARRANGED FOR O'NEAL TRANSPORTATION TO REPAIR LEAK.  A MR. BUFDY FRAZIER OF O'NEAL TRANSPORTATION EXAMINED THE TANK CAR ON 3/25/93 AND FOUND THAT A BAD FLANGE GASKET ON THE UNLOADING DISCHARGE TUBE HAD CAUSED THE LEAK.  THE TANK CAR WAS REPAIRED AT 12:10 PM ON MARCH 25, 1992.  RICHARD MITCHELL FROM KOPPERS COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED THAT CAR WAS RELEASED FOR UNLOADING.

column168: PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE, STAIN AND ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, SEVERAL AEROSOL CANS AND HOUSEHOLD GOODS.  ONE (1) 16 OUNCE CAN OF FLEA AND TICK SPRAY LEAKED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS FROM THE TOP.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELING ON THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE TO INDICATE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE CONTAINED INSIDE.  A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION WAS CONTACTED AT 310/215-2280 WHERE SPECIAL AGENTS BOB NOWLAND AND RHONDA HATMAKER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

CREW PERSONNEL NOTED A STRONG AMMONIA COMING FROM ACFX 19926 IN DONALDSONVILLE, LA.  CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED.  REGIONAL MANAGER T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SECURED WITH SEAL AMPRO FERTILIZER 021852.  SEAL WAS REMOVED AND FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS COMING FROM BENEATH THE BASE OF THE "B" LIQUID VALVE.  ATTEMPTS TO SECURE THE LEAK WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  MANAGER ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, S. MISTRETTA AND M. MCKAY. column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) D. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS (MTO) B. MILTON THAT TRAIN CREW HAD NOTED NATX 38152 LEAKING AND HAD SET IT OUT.  MTO MILTON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A STEADY STREAM OF PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE "A" END SAFETY VALVE.  THE LIQUID WAS RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR.  ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES WERE CONTACTED AND PROVIDED A TANK TRUCK TO REDUCE THE LADING. APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TANK CAR AND STORED IN TANK TRUCK PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  TANK CAR WAS SET INTO CALNEV FACILITY, PENDING INSTRUCTIONS AS CHEVRON.  CHEMTREC, NEVADA DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AND THE NEVADA PUBLIC SERVICE COMMISSION WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: SPECIALIST, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (SCTS) WAS NOTIFIED THAT FRA INSPECTOR B. MARRIOTT HAD FOUND GATX 18585 LEAKING PRODUCT DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION.  SCTS RODABOUGH CONTACTED B. BRUNSKILL (MTO) AT ROCK SPRINGS. MTO BRUNSKILL REPORTED THAT A TECHNICIAN FROM VAN WATER & ROGERS HAD RESPONDED AND ATTEMPTED TO REPAIR CAR.  INSPECTION HAD DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET TO REPAIR CAR.  INSPECTION HAD DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT OPERABLE.  THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE VAN WATERS & ROGERS PLANT FOR UNLOADING (UNLOADED THROUGH DISCHARGE PIPE).  APPARENTLY THE OPERATING ROD HAD BECOME DISENGEAGED FROM THE OPERATING SCREW AND THE ROD FELL INTO THE TANK.  CAR WAS SENT TO THE SHOP FOR REPAIR.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE BS&B 100 PSI, FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW BS&B 100 PSI, AND APPLIED SEAL UP-C 54692.  ACCOUNT OF DISC DETERIORATION AND PAINT CORROSION ON BOTH LEFT AND RIGHT SIDES OF CAR, BELEIVE THAT DISC FAILED BEFORE SWITCH MOVE AT CHEYENNE.  CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND 2 INCH VENT, WHICH IS LOCATED ON WORKING PLATFORM.  STAN ANDERSON OF KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING ROLL-BY INSPECTIONS, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (CTS) C.L. HILL NOTED TGAX 121014 HAVING LIQUID ON TOP OF CAR AROUND SAFETY VENT.  TRAIN WAS STOPPED AND MTCS HILL INSPECTED THE CAR. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE FDI, 100 PSI, FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED.  A NEW FDI, 100 PSI, FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INSTALLED IN THE SAFETY VENT WHICH WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE THE WORKING PLATFORM.  VENT WAS BOLTED ON SIX INCH NOZZLE AND THE BAFFLE WAS LOCATED BETWEEN THE BASE OF THE SAFETY VENT AND THE TOP OF THE SIX INCH NOZZLE. column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: SETTTEGAST YARD SWITCH CREW NOTED SCMX 1220 HAD LIQUID LEAKING AROUND THE TOP FITTINGS.  MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS (MTO) PENNINGTON HAD THE CAR SET OUT FOR INSPECTION.  MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION (CTS) WAS OUT OF THE AREA AND SHELL CHEMICAL (PASADENA, TX) WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC TO RESPOND.  SHELL REPRESENTATIVES (BOZE & MATTOX) RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID HAD COME FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE FOUND NO DEFECTS.  CAR HAD NO PRESSURE ON IT AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT IT WAS NOT OVERLOADED.  THE RELIEF VALVE HAD NEW BOLTS ON IT AND SUSPECTED THAT IT HAD RECENTLY BEEN REPLACED AND MAY BE DEFECTIVE.  A SECOND TEAM FROM SHELL (OLIVER LEDEAUX) AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM RESCAR INSPECTED THE VALVE AGAIN ON 03/21/93.  NO DEFECTS COULD BE NOTED.  THE O RINGS WERE REPLACED AS A PRECAUTION (SAFETY VALVE HAD BEEN TESTED ON 02/08/93.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) D. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS (MTO) R. PERRY THAT CREW HAD NOTED A LEAKING TANK CAR IN TRAIN OGYR-19.  MTO PERRY INSPECTED CAR AND LIQUID PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE AREA.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND MCTS COOPER RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET IN THE COVER PLATE WAS WORN WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE DURING MOVEMENT. GORE-TEX MATERIAL WAS APPLIED ON THE TOP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE TO SECURE THE CAR (SPECIFIC TYPE OF GASKET WAS NOT AVAILABLE).  ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INSURE THE REPAIRS WERE ADEQUATE TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. CAR WAS FOUND TO BE SECURE AND WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC, CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

DURING THE COURSE OF A ROUTINE INSPECTION, SA/HM DECHANT NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK FROM THE AREA OF THE MANWAY.  INSPECTION DISCLOSED SOME MATERIAL ALSO ON THE TOP OF THE CAR IN THE AREA OF THE MANWAY.  SOURCE WAS THE FRANGIBLE DISC TYPE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY, MOUNTED ON THE CENTER OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A THREE-BOLT TYPE DISC HOUSING; ONE BOLT WAS FOUND SLIGHTLY LOOSE, ANOTHER LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  THIS ALLOWED HOUSING TO MOVE, DISPLACING DISC AND ALLOWING PRODUCT TO PASS.  DISC (100#, BS&B SS/TEFLON) WAS REPOSITIONED AND ASSEMBLY TIGHTENED.  NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  WAYBILL LISTED CHEMTREC AS CONTACT.  DURING SUBQSEQUENT CONVERSATION, CHEMTREC REPRESENTATIVE ADVISED THAT THE SHIPPER (LINCHEM) WAS NOT REGISTERED WITH CHEMTREC.  CONSIGNEE FURNISHED A NUMBER THROUGH WHICH SHIPPER CONTACT COULD BE MADE.  DETAILS OF BOTH THE LOOSE FITTING AND THE DISCREPANCY OVER THE EMERGENCY TELEPHONE NUMBER WERE THEN ADDRESSED WITH THE SHIPPER, AT WHICH TIME IT WAS LEARNED THAT LINCHEM HAD CHANGED THEIR COMPANY NAME TO ASHTA CHEMICAL.  THE BILLING CARRIER HAD APPARENTLY NOT YET INCORPORATED THIS CHANGE INTO THEIR BILLING PROCEDURES.  CHEMTREC WAS THE CORRECT CONTACT.  SHIPPER WILL HANDLE DIRECTLY WITH BILLING PERSONNEL FOR CORRECTION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Water Damage
column168: ON 03/24/93 SPECIALIST M. KELLY WITH THE CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION DEPT WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN HARLINGEN, TX.  THE CAR DEPT. IN HARLINGEN ADVISED KELLY THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD ARRIVED IN THE YARD WITH A WET SPOT, ABOUT THREE FEET ACROSS THE TOP OF THE CAR NEAR THE MANWAY OPENING.  UPON ARRIVAL IN HARLINGEN, TX., KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS CRACKED AND MISSING A PIECE ABOUT EIGHT INCHES LONG.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT ALL THE SWING BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER WERE LESS THAT WRENCH TIGHT.  KELLY REPLACED THE GASKET WITH GORE TEX JOINT SEALANT AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED ALL THE SWING BOLTS, MAKING THE CAR READY FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORATION.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT FOUR OTHER CARS TRAVELING WITH THIS CAR FROM THE SAME SHIPPER HAD MULTIPLE EXCEPTIONS FOUND UPON INSPECTION.  SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE BOTH NOTIFIED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY WICHITA, KANSAS YARDMASTER FLOYD HURST ADVISING CAR FOREMAN REPORTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLEY CAP.  MR. STINE'S INSPECTON DEVELOPED THE RATE OF DRIP WAS 40 DROPS PER MINUTED.  THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE STUFFING BOX COVER WAS OFF AND HANGING BY SAFETY CHAIN, THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED 1/4TH TURN WHICH SECURED THE LEAK.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON STUFFING BOX WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  RELIEVED INTERNAL PRESSURE AND OPENED CAR NOTING A 10 INCH WIDE TRACK OF PRODUCT IN BOTTOM OF CAR.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED, THEIR REPORT 21045.  MR LONG INDICATED THERE IS NO INFORMATION THIS SHIPPER IS A MEMBER OF CHEMTREC AND NO SHIPPING INFORMATION WAS FOUND. SHIPPER CONTACTED 03/29/93 BY MR STINE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY (MCTS) D.C. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATION D. ERTLE THAT CREW NOTED GATX 300417 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING OPERATION.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND MCTS COOPER RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD OPERATED PRIOR TO ARRIVING YERMO WHICH HAD ALLOWED SEVERAL GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE TOP AND DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR AND SOLIDIFY. NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED ON THE SAFETY VALVE.  SAFETY VALVE WAS PROPERLY SEATED.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND VALVES WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRNSPORATION SAFETY (MCTS) D. ALM WAS NOTIFIED BY SPECIAL AGENT/HAZAROUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) B. BALLANCE THAT TRAILER APLS 27715 WAS LEAKING AT UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL TRAILER FACILITY.  MCTS ALM RESPONDED AND CONTACTED OH MATERIALS ENROUTE FOR ASSISTANCE.  UPON ARRIVAL ENTIRE AREA HAD BEEN CLOSED DOWN BY THE OAKLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AFTER MEETING WITH APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL, THE WEST END OF THE TRAILER FACILITY WAS OPEN FOR TRAFFIC.  OH MATERIAL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED ONE 55 GALLON DRUM LEAKING. THE DRUM HAD RUBBED AGAINST THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER AND HAD DEVELOPED A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM JUST ABOVE THE FIRST RING.  ALSO, THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED BY OH MATERIAL AND TRAILER WAS RELOADED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED BY THE SHIPPER.  CHEMTREC AND ALL APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON 03/31/93 REEDER WAS MAKING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AT LLOYD YARD IN SPRING, TEXAS WHEN HE DISCOVERED THE FRANGIBLE DISC ON THE ABOVE CAR HAD FAILED.  THE DISC WAS A BS&B, 100PSI. WHILE UNLOADING AIRCRAFT AT MAF, THE RAMP AGENT DISCOVERED A WET BOX (CHECKED AS BAGGAGE), WITH A SMELL OF FUEL.  THE BIN FLOOR WAS WET WITH THE LIQUID.  THE BOX WAS OPENED AND A HALF FULL GALLON CAN OF COLEMAN FUEL WAS DISCOVERED.  THE AIRCRAFT BIN WAS CLEANED OF ALL LIQUID BEFORE BEING DISPATCHED FOR ANOTHER FLIGHT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: A CONRAIL YARD INSPECTOR NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE FLANGE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF UTLX 201023.  THE TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AT 1108 AND CALLED BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVE INSPECTOR D.M. HEALY TO ASSIST.  MR. HEALY FOUND A RECENTLY SERVICED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE THAT HAD EITHER A BAD GASKET OR WAS IMPROPERLY SEATED;  HE COULD NOT STOP THE LEAK. MR HEALY CONFERRED WITH MR. JOHN HOWELL, OF THE SHIPPER, AND THEY AGREED TO TRANSFER THE LOAD TO TRUCKS.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SA/HM) J. JARA WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER REAZ 230078 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT.  SA/HM JARA RESPONDED AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  UPON ARRIVAL, SA/HM JARA MET WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM, ALAMEDA HEALTH ENVIRONMENTAL DEPT MEMBERS, FRA AND US COAST GUARD.  AGENCIES WERE CONDUCTING INSPECTION WHEN INSPECTOR J NELSON MOVED CARTON AND NOTED HYDROCHLORIC ACID LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE CONTAINERS. INSPECTOR IMMEDIATELY WASHED HANDS TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUE.  SA/JM JARA CONTACTED OH MATERIAL WHO RESPONDED.  TRAILER WAS CHECKED BY HEALTH SERVICE RADIOLOGIC HEALTH BRANCH DUE TO THE TRAILER CONTAINING MATERIAL.  TRAILER WAS FOUND TO BE CLEAR AND OH MATERIAL PRESONNEL CHECKED REMAINING CONTENTS FOR LEAKAGE.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS PLACED IN A OVERPACK DRUM AND LEFT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  NO OTHER LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE FOUND.  TRAILER WAS CABLE LOCKED (B4 007267) AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.
PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM, PACKAGE WAS RTS & DAMAGE REPORT SENT TO DIC.

column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) C. L. HILL WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREW HAD NOTED A STRONG ODOR FROM TANK CAR GATX 47837.  MCTS HILL RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE MIDLAND 1 1225 SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS LEAKING.  TANK CAR PRESSURE WAS 120 PSI AND LATER DROPPED TO 100 PSI.  REGIONAL MANAGER BOB STINE AND BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES FIELD INSPECTOR, AL MATY RESPONDED WITH NEW BUNA N "O" RINGS WHICH WERE SUCCESSFULLY CHANGED, SECURING LEAKING SAFETY VALVE.  THE "O" RINGS REMOVED FROM THE SAFETY VALVE WERE OLD AND REQUIRED SCRAPING FROM VALVE RETAINER.  TEST DATES ON CAR SHOWED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS TESTED ON 03/24/93. SEAL CF 014147 WAS REMOVED FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND UP S 799622 WAS APPLIED UPON COMPLETION.  BILL GASSON OF CHEMTREC (REPORT 21126) AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE DON AYERS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY JACK FURLONG THAT ROLL OFF/ON CONTAINER UPCU 4100311 ON FLAT CAR VTTX 95241 WAS NOTED TO HAVE A GREENISH COLORED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR TAIL GATE.  CAR WAS BEING SET TO TRACK 510 FOR INSPECTION.  CONTACTED CHIEF INSPECTOR AAR, MR. A.D. MATY WHO AGREED TO RESPOND AND HIS INSPECTION REVEALED THE FOLLOWING:  A LIQUID WHICH APPEARED TO BE WATER, DRIPPING ALONG THE LENGTH OF THE TAIL GATE, WITH AN ACCUMULATION OF A GREENISH POWDERY RESIDUE WHICH WAS COLLECTING ON THE END STILL, COUPLER POCKET AND CENTER STILL OF THE FLAT CAR. HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST INDICATED THE MATERIAL WAS FURTHER DESCRIBED;  RQ, (F006) (WASTE WATER TREATMENT SLUDGE FROM ELECTROPLATING, RQ 10 LBS.  SHIPMENT ORIGINATED AT CADDILLAC MOTOR CAR DIVISION, DETROIT, MI.  MR. MATY OPENED THE END TOP SLIDING COVER, AND NOTED ABOUT 8 TO 12 INCHES OF ICE ON FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER. THE BULK WASTE (A PILE APPROX 10 FEET LONG, 6 FEET WIDE AND ONE TO TWO FEET DEEP) HAD BEEN DUMPED ON TOP OF THE ICE.  THE ICE WAS MELTING, CAUSING THE WATER WITH SOME WASTE TO FLOW FROM BEHIND THE TAIL GATE.  IT APPEEARS THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN DURING A SNOW STORM, WHICH RESULTED IN THE ICE FORMATION.  (CONTINUED ON ATTACHMENT).

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.H. SMITH WAS NOTIFIED BY STO MENDOZA THAT TANK CAR GATX 12907 WAS RELEASING A STRONG ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OLD AND BRITTLE AND NOT ABLE TO CONTAIN THE SLIGHT INCREASE IN PRESSURE DUE TO A RISE IN AMBIENT TEMPERATURE.  AFTER ATTEMPTING TO STOP THE VAPOR LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE MANWAY COVER, SSA/HM SMITH REPLACED THE GAKSET WITH TEMPORARY GASKET MATERIAL.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE BILL CLOSE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column14: E HWY 14 N OF HWY 126 PLACENTA
column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGING FAILURE.  TEXACO TRUCKING INC. WAS LOADING OIL INTO CARGO TANK AND OIL BEGAN TO "FOAM" OUT OF THE CARGO TANK, SPILLING APPROXIMATLEY 10 BARRELLS OF OIL TO THE GROUND.  INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING RAINSTORM, AND OIL WAS CARRIED TO A DRAINAGE CHANNEL.  OIL AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS COLLECTED AND WILL BE SENT TO A NON-HAZARDOUS LANDFILL.  SITE HAS BEEN CLEANED UP.  INCIDENT WAS REPORTED BY TELEPHONE TO NRC (CASE #164528), OES (CALIF. OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES) (CASE #27428), LOS ANGELES REGIONAL WATER QUALITY CONTROL BOARD (J. LEWIS), DIVISION OF OIL & GAS.

column168: THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED LEAKING IN FEEDER #294442 (ORIGIN - BURTONVILLE, MD) IN BAY 4 - ON THE DAYSORT.  SEVERAL PACKAGE (OUTER CARTONS) WERE CONTAMINATED - BUT CONTENTS NOT AFFECTED.  DIR #5818622 - TEMP ID#(03-26-07D) THE DAMAGED CARTONS SOILED WITH MATERIAL AND THE ORIGINAL 5 GALLON CONTAINER (TOP DENTED) WERE DISPOSED OF THRU MALLINCKRODT DISPOSAL - BALANCE REPACKED IN NEW 5 GALLON CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Overfilled; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON MARCH 6,1993, AT ABOUT 0345, OUR DRIVER, GREG HYLAND HAD A 30 GALLON GASOLINE SPILL WHILE UNLOADING AT CLARK #1666, 1655 DEKALB AVE., SYCAMORE, ILLINOIS 60178.  WHILE UNLOADING INTO 2 TANKS THAT ARE PLUMBED TOGETHER, ONE FILLED UP SO HE SWITCHED TO THE OTHER FILL.  THIS TANK THEN FILLED UP AND PRODUCT FLOWED FROM THE FIRST TANK OUT ONTO THE DRIVE, BECAUSE THE CAP WASN'T REPLACED ON THE TANK.  PRODUCT IN THE HOSE CONTINUED TO COME OUT.  THIS DRIVER HAD BEEN TERMINATED DUE TO NOT FOLLOWING UNLOADING PROCEDURES.
LOOSE CAP DISCOVERED IN PACKAGE IN LOAD AREA.  CAP TIGHTENED AND PACKAGE FORWARDED.
